<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-179-204  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 179 204.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 11 1989 v3 n15 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>More communications to come. (Apple connectivity announcements)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Swartz, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple MacDFT (Circuit board) (product introduction)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     Communications Boards-CardsProduct IntroductionEthernetEnhancementsX.400 ProtocolCommunications EquipmentProduct DevelopmentBusiness Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>More communications to comeandM;The communications product announcements that Apple has scheduled June 7 areexpected to touch off a series of networking-related introductions over thenext year to 18 months.andM;* MacDFT, a communications card based on the Macintosh Coprocessor Platformand designed for emulation of IBM 3270 terminals, could be a year away.andP;  LikeTokenTalk, the card is in high demand at Fortune 1,000 companies that dependheavily on IBM mainframes.andP;  MacDFT will be able to run stand-alone sessionsor as a 3278 cluster controller, sources said.andM;* Apple is &quot;seriously considering&quot; an internal Ethernet port in futureMacintosh systems, according to Henri Aebischer, Apple's director ofnetworking and communicaitons product marketing.andP;  The port, which wouldreside on the system's motherboard, should boost data transfer rates by atleast 500 percent.andP;  Macs currently require adapter cards, priced at $500 to$700, to run at Ethernet speeds.andM;In principle, Ethernet can transfer data at 10 Mbits per second (Mbps) -- 40times faster than LocalTalk's 230-Kbps rate -- although the performancedifferential is less dramatic in real-life situations.andM;* Final technical specifications outlining products that integrate Apple andDigital Equipment Corp. computers and networks should be announced at Apple'sdevelopers conference next month.andP;  Those products, however, won't beavailable until at least the fall.andM;* Work is proceeding on an X.400 electronic-mail system at Apple's Cupertino,Calif., headquarters and at its Research and Development Center in Paris.andP;  Inaddition, products incorporating several other international data protocols,including X.25 for packet switching and V.32 for full-duplex 9,600-bps datatransfer, are reportedly under development.andO;</TEXT></DOC>